      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the onion base",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat {{rapeseed-oil}} of oil in a large, heavy pan over medium heat. Add {{onion}} chopped onions and cook for 12 minutes until deep golden. Add {{garlic}} of grated garlic and {{ginger-root}} of grated ginger; cook for 3 minutes. Add {{chilli-powder}} of chilli powder, {{cumin-ground}} of cumin, {{coriander-ground}} of ground coriander and {{turmeric}} of turmeric; stir and fry for 2 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bhuno the masala",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes. Raise the heat to medium-high and cook, stirring frequently, for 15 to 18 minutes. The sauce will bubble vigorously, then thicken, then begin to dry out. Keep cooking until the tomatoes have broken down completely and the oil separates around the edges of the masala. The mixture should look almost dry.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add the chicken and finish",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Add {{chicken-thigh}} of chicken pieces and {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt. Stir to coat in the masala. Add 150 ml of water. Cover and cook over medium-low heat for 20 minutes until the chicken is cooked through and the sauce clings thickly. Stir in {{garam-masala}} of garam masala and cook for 2 more minutes uncovered. Scatter coriander to serve.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Troubleshooting",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "intro": null,
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "The bhunoing stage is critical. Cook until the tomato is completely dry and the oil separates; only then add the chicken.",
              "cause": "Masala not reduced far enough before adding chicken.",
              "symptom": "Sauce too liquid, not clinging"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Fry the dry spices in oil for at least 2 minutes before adding the tomatoes. They should smell cooked and aromatic, not raw and powdery.",
              "cause": "Ground spices not cooked out in the fat.",
              "symptom": "Spices taste raw"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Chicken thighs take about 20 minutes over medium-low heat with the lid on. Check at 15 minutes.",
              "cause": "Cooked too long after the bhunoing stage.",
              "symptom": "Chicken dry"
            }
          ],
          "heading": "Common problems"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bhuna is a staple of the British curry house, where it usually appears as the 'dry' option on the menu. Made at home, it is a faster curry than a slow-braised rogan josh and a better weeknight option: the bhunoing technique concentrates the flavours quickly without needing long simmering. Serve with basmati rice or a plain paratha.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
